 running inference on realistic transaction patterns can verify it actually identifies the pattern as stated.","test_description":"Construct a series of 3–5 realistic transactions representing fraud pattern: small amounts ($50–$200 each), different merchant categories, rapid succession (within 2 hours), geographically dispersed (e.g., New York → London → Tokyo). Extract features from this transaction sequence and invoke the real risk model. Verify fraud probability exceeds the model's fraud threshold (e.g., >0.7). Contrast with a legitimate transaction sequence of same structure but normal geographies/timing—verify low fraud probability.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.1,"System":0,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The velocity check in the scoring model correctly counts the number of transactions within the configured time window per user.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Velocity check must query user transaction history and count within a time window. A mock transaction retrieval would hide real failures: fetches wrong user, off-by-one in time boundary, queries wrong collection, time comparison logic reversed. Testing the full counting pipeline—retrieving real or test transaction data from a database and verifying the count—requires integration with a test database or realistic data fixture.","test_description":"Insert 5 test transactions for a single user: 3 within the configured time window (e.g., last 60 minutes) and 2 outside. Call velocity check with the configured window. Verify it returns count=3 (only transactions inside window). Test boundary cases: transaction exactly at window start and exactly at window end—verify they are included or excluded per the configured window definition.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A transaction flagged by the risk model but not by the scoring model is still held for review — the models operate as an OR gate, not AND.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This tests pure boolean logic combining two independent model flags. The behavior is 'hold_for_review = scoring_flag OR risk_flag'. A unit test with mocked models (one returns true, one returns false) is sufficient to verify OR logic. Real model behavior does not affect the gate logic—only the individual flag values do, which mocks control. Logic bugs (AND instead of OR, inverted logic, ignored flag) are caught at unit level.","test_description":"Mock the scoring model to return flag=false for a transaction. Mock the risk model to return flag=true for the same transaction. Call the combined fraud detection logic. Verify the transaction is marked as 'held for review'. Verify with opposite flags (scoring=true, risk=false). Verify both flags true and both false cases as well.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.1,"System":0,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The combined output includes both the numeric risk score and the risk model's fraud probability, so the reviewer can see which model flagged the transaction and why.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This tests output structure and data flow—that two values are present and correctly mapped from their model sources. A unit test with mocked models (returning known values) suffices to verify the response body includes both fields with the correct values. Missing field, swapped fields, or incorrect mapping are caught without involving real model behavior. The structure test does not require model inference or database integration.","test_description":"Mock scoring model to return risk_score=75.5. Mock risk model to return fraud_probability=0.82. Call the combined fraud detection system with a test transaction. Verify the response JSON includes both fields: 'risk_score': 75.5 and 'fraud_probability': 0.82. Verify 